{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0e45397c-49b6-4ab7-9502-d208524dd9ca","content":"No repo-specific docs cover this topic. Here's the general guidance:\n\n---\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`**\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — re-run your NativeAOT app. macOS will write a Mach-O core file to `/cores/`.\n\n4. **Check for the dump**:\n   ```bash\n   ls -la /cores/\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** (the macOS-native debugger):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<PID> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternatively, check Apple's CrashReporter** — macOS may automatically capture a `.crash` report in:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n   These contain stack traces but are not full core dumps.\n\n> **Note:** SIP (System Integrity Protection) can block core dump generation for certain binaries. If `/cores/` stays empty, ensure SIP isn't interfering and that the target directory is writable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"edd0eba3-116e-456a-82bc-015422149593","outputTokens":349,"requestId":"6813:1E80:CB6A89:E9F512:69FD4237"},"id":"bacc98fa-41b1-43a1-a08b-d70ddd51b257","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:54:08.956Z","parentId":"31b02567-b569-43b8-8ba1-1114be8795bf"}
